The oft-held premise, at least in the early days of the streaming wars, was=
 that you needed to invest massively in content to drive engagement and sca=
le your platform. Today, Netflix spends more on DTC-only content than any o=
ther company, exceeding $15 billion in global content amortization in 2024.=
 That is nearly $7 billion more than the second largest DTC spender in Disn=
ey, which expensed $8.6 billion in DTC programming amortization in FY 2024.=
 It is also nearly equal to the DTC expenses of WBD, NBCU, and Paramount co=
mbined.

As with most businesses, there are massive benefits to scale in streaming. =
Thus, it should come as no surprise that Netflix manages to sustain its ind=
ustry-leading levels of content spending through its significant lead in gl=
obal scale, which enables it to spread the costs over a bigger base. While =
Netflix spends far more on DTC content than any other company, when we look=
 at content spend per subscriber, we see that Netflix is right in line with=
 Disney and WBD, and our forecast sees this ratio holding relatively steady=
 over the next three years (see Exhibit 11). Peacock and Paramountt, on the=
 other hand, currently spend significantly more than Netflix on a per subsc=
riber basis, in part because their platforms index more towards the U.S. (o=
r in Peacock's case, exclusively to the U.S.) which is one of the more expe=
nsive markets in which to operate, and in part thanks to both platform's he=
avy focus on sports. The ultimate driver, though, is lack of scale.

Because Netflix has more subscribers to spread its content spending across,=
 it can afford to spend more on content. Because it has more content, it dr=
ives better engagement, leading to more subscribers and possibly better pri=
cing power in a virtuous cycle that has played out quite well for the compa=
ny to date.

So far, so good, and very much in line with my expectations. I promise, how=
ever, I'm not here for a victory tour. Rather, it was Nathanson's next poin=
t that I think is worth calling out:

Yet, another underappreciated aspect is this has enabled Netflix, and to a =
lesser extent Disney, to undercut its competitors in terms of monetization.=
 Netflix in 2024 generated less revenue per hour viewed in the U.S. than an=
y other major SVOD platform at just $0.36, of which only $0.34 came out of =
its users' pockets in the form of subscription fees. U.S. Disney+ subscribe=
rs paid $0.40 in 2024 for each hour of viewing (see Exhibit 12).

Yes, it may be an obvious point that a platform with a larger viewership ba=
se to spread its revenue across will naturally have lower revenue per hour,=
 but that is also key to understanding Netflix's success and why its compet=
itors have and will continue to struggle to catch up: Netflix delivers grea=
t value. The average Paramount+ subscriber is paying double in subscription=
 fees for each hour of viewing pleasure compared to the average Netflix sub=
scriber in the U.S.

This makes total sense, and is a worthy extension of Aggregation Theory. Sp=
ecifically, while more subscribers means that Netflix can spend more on con=
tent, thus attracting more subscribers, more content also means that Netfli=
x can drive more engagement on a per-customer basis =E2=80=94 there's just =
more to watch! This, in Netflix's case, provides "permission" to raise pric=
es; Co-CEO Greg Peters said on the recent earnings call the same concept Ne=
tflix executives espouse on every earnings call:

Our pricing philosophy hasn't changed. It's pretty much the same as we've t=
alked about for the last several years. Of course, we look to continue to p=
rovide more value to our members, seeking to wisely invest to increase the =
variety and quality of our entertainment offering. And then we listen to th=
ose members. We listen for signals like engagement, retention, acquisition.=
 There's more secondary signals as well, all to tell us when we've achieved=
 that increase in value. And when we've done that, then we ask them to pay =
a bit more to keep that virtuous cycle going.

This principle extends to non-subscription businesses as well; consider a s=
ocial network: the more compelling the content, the more time users spend, =
which means the more ads they can see. This isn't, to be fair to me, exactl=
y a novel insight; I said in the original Aggregation Theory Article ( http=
