This has fundamentally changed the plane of competition: no longer do distr=
ibutors compete based upon exclusive supplier relationships, with consumers=
/users an afterthought. Instead, suppliers can be commoditized leaving cons=
umers/users as a first order priority. By extension, this means that the mo=
st important factor determining success is the user experience: the best di=
stributors/aggregators/market-makers win by providing the best experience, =
which earns them the most consumers/users, which attracts the most supplier=
s, which enhances the user experience in a virtuous cycle.

What I was not explicit about =E2=80=94=C2=A0and really hadn't fully consid=
ered, until I read Nathanson's piece =E2=80=94 is how directly this is link=
ed to monetization. Netflix doesn't just have more buying power because it =
has the most customers; it has the most pricing power as well. A better use=
r experience =E2=80=94 which Aggregators have a structural advantage in pro=
viding =E2=80=94 is worth paying for! That, by extension, means that the Ag=
gregator's virtuous cycle isn't only a function of having ever more subscri=
bers, but also in the related capacity to charge each of those subscribers =
more; the advantage compounds.

